## Testing philosophy
- Test observable behavior and user-visible outcomes, not implementation trivia.
- Prefer table-driven or parameterized tests when they improve clarity.
- Keep tests deterministic; avoid reliance on real time, network, or flaky ordering unless isolated in integration tests.

## Unit tests
- Keep mocks at true boundaries (HTTP, storage, browser APIs).
- Prefer testing pure helpers and hooks with realistic inputs.
- Use testing-library patterns that resemble user interaction (roles, labels) over brittle selectors.

## Integration and E2E tests
- Cover important workflows and API contract assumptions with realistic fixtures.
- Avoid hidden environmental assumptions; document required env for integration runs.
- E2E tests should focus on critical paths; keep them maintainable and parallel-safe where possible.

## Visual and accessibility
- When the project uses visual regression or a11y checks in CI, keep snapshots and rules stable and intentional.

## Quality gates
- New behavior should include tests or a clear rationale when tests are impractical (e.g. thin wiring only).
- Prefer fast unit tests for tight feedback; reserve heavy E2E for high-value flows.
- Keep the test suite fast enough for frequent local execution.
